[Assam has been a state of very active JE virus transmission in recent years and currently a state with the most AES and JE cases in India. Although the previous report from Assam indicated a decline in JE and AES cases, the above case numbers clearly indicate that cases of JE and AES continue and are increasing currently. The planned ambitious JE vaccination campaign should be helpful in reducing cases of JE disease.

As mentioned in many previous ProMED posts, the issue of the etiology of AES has been under discussion for a long time. AES has continued to be attributed to various etiologies, including Reye syndrome-like disease, possible JE, enterovirus infection from polluted water, heatstroke, scrub typhus (_Orientia tsutsugamushi_), and intoxication from lychee fruit consumption. Dr T Jacob John noted that hypoglycemic encephalopathy is triggered by litchi consumption. A recent publication states that dengue virus is one of the 3 commonest agents identified in AES, but existing surveillance for AES does not include routine testing for dengue. - Mod.TY

HealthMap/ProMED map of Assam State, India: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=8699380,299]
